{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645318"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:17:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:17:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18107"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18107"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73549"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10821"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18107"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59018"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"11255"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25193"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73549"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is transmitted through the suprascapular foramen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vagus nerve","Axillary nerve","Long thoracic nerve","Accessory nerve","Suprascapular nerve"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuprascapular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E passes through the suprascapular foramen, which is formed by the suprascapular notch and the superior transverse scapular ligament. This nerve innervates the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles, which are responsible for shoulder abduction and external rotation. Injury or compression of this nerve can lead to weakness in these movements, as seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a cranial nerve that innervates structures in the thorax and abdomen, not the shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles and is not transmitted through the suprascapular foramen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elong thoracic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the serratus anterior muscle and is not associated with the suprascapular foramen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccessory nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles and does not pass through the suprascapular foramen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The suprascapular foramen transmits the suprascapular nerve, which innervates the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles.","The suprascapular nerve is important for shoulder movement and stability."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59018"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18107"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59018"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T00:06:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T00:07:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10821"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73549"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":